Brett applied for VO membership recently with an OSG cert on July 1,
2014, and as far as I can tell, went through the sign-in
form linked above and should have seen and clicked &#34;yes&#34; on the AUP
linked immediately above.   The VOMS admin interface
says the AUP was signed 160 days ago and it will expire in 204 days.

He has an older membership using his KCA identity.  The AUP on this
expired January 30, 2014, and his
membership was suspended.  On January 30, 2014, more than
half of the users in the LBNE VO had their AUP expire and were
suspended.  This is largely due to the old version of VOMS
giving users only 24 hours (regardless of holidays or weekends) between
being notified and being suspended.  Eileen
and I complained about this since many of our collaborators have
difficulty obtaining KCA certificates on their non-Fermilab
computers and the 24-hour window was not enough time for busy users to
divert their attention to figuring out how to
install KCA certs.   I re-instated the suspended accounts back in
January to keep people working.
VOMS was upgraded in May 2014 or thereabouts to a system that gives two
weeks advance notice and no ability for admins
to update users&#39; AUP signing.    So some users may not have signed an
AUP since their initial signin and may have forgotten,
<div id='show_362145041' class=''><button class="btn">Show More</button></div><div class='detail hidden' id='detail_362145041'>and this will change the next time their AUP&#39;s expire (late January 2015
will see lots of expirations).

All users too should also be renewing their Fermilab computer
accounts once a year, which requires
review of and agreement to the Fermilab computing policy.

<a href='http&#58;//security.fnal.gov/policies/cpolicy.html' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//security.fnal.gov/policies/cpolicy.html</a>

